				Two unique facts about Scotland
			</h3>
		</div>
			
		
		<div class="d-flex justify-content-center">
			<p class="show-text">
				Robert Burns is Scotland’s most treasured poet and writer, and is celebrated world wide. He died at the age of 37 in 1796 after having written many poems and songs that are known all over the world. Some of his most famous poems
and songs are “Auld Lang Syne”, “A Red, Red Rose”, and “To a Mouse”. Every January there is a celebration in his honor. This tradition was started by his close friends after his death and still goes on today. During the celebration the traditional meal of “Haggis” is served. Haggis is a meal made with sheep’s lungs, heart, and liver mixed with oatmeal and spices, cooked and served inside a sheep’s stomach. The meal is served with Scotch and Robert Burns works are usually cited after the meal.
			</p>
		</div>
		
		
	
		
		
		<div class="d-flex justify-content-center">
			<p class="show-text">
				Highland games are events held in Spring and Summer since the 11th century to celebrate the Scottish and Celtic culture. While the event is mostly about heavy activities there is also cultural entertainments and exhibits that portrays the Scottish culture as well as pipe band music and dancing. There are many amazing events such as Caber toss, which is a long wooden post thrown as far and as straight as possible. Other events include Stone put, Scottish Hammer throw, and Sheaf toss.

			</p>
		</div>
		
		
		
		<div class="d-flex justify-content-center">
			<figure>
				<img class="show-img1" src="http://www.visitscotland.com/cms-images/events/tug-o-war-blair-atholl-highlanders?view=Standard">
