		<div class="d-flex justify-content-center">
			<h3 class="show-factsh3">
				Two unique facts about Wales
			</h3>
		</div>
			
		
		<div class="d-flex justify-content-center">
			<p class="show-text">
				The last prince of Wales Llwelyn Ein Llyw Olaf died defending his country against Edward I of England in 1282 at the Battle of Orewin Bridge. His severed head was taken to Edward by a horseman who put it on his lance. They set the head on the lance over the gate of the Tower and London and it stayed there for 15 years. The last resting place for Llwelyn’s body is not known.
			</p>
		</div>
		
		
	
		
		
		<div class="d-flex justify-content-center">
			<p class="show-text">
				Major Walter Clopton Wingfield was a British Army officer and a Welsh inventor. He is accepted to be the inventor of lawn tennis. He had patented the New and Improved game of indoor Tennis to outdoor Tennis and sold packages of rubber balls, poles and nets to the public.

			</p>
		</div>
		
		
		
		<div class="d-flex justify-content-center">
			<figure>
				<img class="show-img1" src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/0d/Lawn-tennis-Prang-1887.jpeg/1200px-Lawn-tennis-Prang-1887.jpeg">
				<span class="d-flex justify-content-center">
					<em><figcaption>Major Walter Clopton Wingfield invented lawn tennis</figcaption></em>
				</span>
