		</div>
		
		
		
		
		
	
		<div class="d-flex justify-content-center">
			<h3 class="show-factsh3">
				Two unique facts about England
			</h3>
		</div>
			
		
		
		<div class="d-flex justify-content-center">
			<p class="show-text">
				There have been many influential English writers, but the most widely known one is William Shakespeare (1564-1616). Shakespeare wrote 39 plays and 154 sonnets. His early works are comedies like The Taming of the Shrew and Midsummer Night’s Dream, and historical dramas like Richard III and Henry VI. His later works were tragedies like Romeo and Juliet, and Hamlet. Although Shakespeare wasn’t respected a lot in his lifetime, he did receive some praise for his works. After his death, two of his friends gathered most of his works into a book called First Folio and published it. Shakespeare’s unique writing style and his creative words made a lasting impressing on literature and theater. In fact Shakespeare added 1,700 words to the English dictionary like lackluster, deafening, and gossip.
			</p>
		</div>
		
		
	
		
		
		<div class="d-flex justify-content-center">
			<p class="show-text">
				Henry VIII was a king of England between 1509-47. He was known for drastic changes to the English Constitution during his reign. He was also known as the Father of the Royal Navy. However, he was most famous for his six wives. In fact
his decision to annul his first marriage led eventually to the English Reformation. He separated the Church of England from papal authority by dissolving all covenants and monasteries and declaring himself the Head of Church of England. He was regarded as one of the most charismatic of the English rulers. He died at a rather young age of 55 due to complications from his excessive weight.

			</p>
		</div>
		
		
		
